{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a228afa7-f8d8-414a-a052-9601fc4e9ee4","content":"Neither — use **`dotnet watch`**.\n\n- `dotnet watch` monitors your source files and automatically rebuilds/reruns when changes are detected. That's the hot reload experience.\n- `dotnet test` and `dotnet run` are one-shot commands — they don't watch for file changes.\n\nFor a test project like yours, run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test\n```\n\nThis will re-run your tests automatically whenever you save a file change.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"44f6eccd-9ee1-4ed1-8aff-1a12c5c7dd1e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about hot reload in .NET - specifically whether to use `dotnet test` or `dotnet run` to benefit from hot reload. Let me look at the project files to understand the context.","outputTokens":166,"requestId":"7C2A:29C906:2814E36:2C83B2A:69F94A68"},"id":"33bbb0b0-2a42-48c4-aac7-a4342d70a47d","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:39:57.683Z","parentId":"b2cc35f1-9696-44fb-9937-3608277487c1"}
